history.content:
Computer Science 161 Covid Instruction plans

CS161 is being designed for a hybrid model for Fall 2020: Those who wish to attend on campus can do so and those who wish to be purely remote can do so.  It is entirely up to the student to select which they prefer.

Background and risk assessment:

The University appears committed to a hybrid in-person and remote model, where small classes can be held in person but all large lectures and exams must be remote and we must actively support remote students.  Additionally there will be a 100% mask-wearing requirement on campus.  I also assume the University will have some internal contact-tracing infrastructure deployed and do other little things (add seat covers to the toilets, set all HVAC systems to only draw outside air).

From a risk assessment to our student population this appears reasonable.  Source control by proper mandatory mask wearing works and this rule will be strictly enforced.  Any student who refuses to wear a mask in an in-person CS161 environment will be reported to the student conduct office: not wearing a mask is a decision which puts others at risk and will not be tolerated.

Additionally the student population is generally in good shape: as more data comes in it is clear there is an almost exponential relationship between age and severity.  Children don’t seem to get infected or spread it, while young adults get infected and can spread it, they don’t seem to suffer particularly bad symptoms in most cases.  Combined with the internal restrictions, we should not see spread within the student population itself and if we do I would assume the University would effectively shift to remote-only.

We need to take extra effort to protect staff and faculty, as risks start to rise to a level of concern when people are above 40, get significant above 50, and downright terrifying for those over 60.  Since students will return to their homes after the semester, we can’t allow internal spread even amongst the low risk student population.  Combined with students importing the COVID policies from all across the country this risk needs to be considered.

Additionally everybody’s personal risk comfort is variable and needs to be considered.  Each person’s risk from participating should be the minimum of the necessary risk and their personal assessment.

The benefits are substantial.  For some students live discussion, and particularly live office hours, are of substantial benefit as you can simply convey much more information, much more quickly, in person than through a teleconference solution like Zoom.

TA choice.

A TA can choose whether they want to be a hybrid TA or a purely remote TA.  This decision will need to be made before the start of the semester as it matters on scheduling.  If a TA decides they need to shift to be a remote TA midway through the semester we will attempt to accommodate the change.

Lecture

Lecture will be a combined in-person/zoom live lecture which will also be recorded as a webcast.  The physical attendance will be limited to the University maximum for an in-person class in the room used, and those students who wish to attend in person must attend regularly and be willing to both ask and answer questions, since the limited capacity means the audience must be the population most likely to benefit from interactivity and/or most likely to improve the overall lecture since questions from the audience are a critical portion of live lectures.

The zoom live broadcast will also have a chat for those who wish to ask questions, and students in the live audience can use the zoom chat if they prefer to ask the questions in textual form.

Discussion

Discussion sections will be in two categories: zoom based and in-person.  If a student wants an in-person discussion section they should attend regularly and there will be an enrollment confirmation before the first discussion.  If a student would rather participate only in zoom based discussion this is no longer a requirement.  The types of discussion sections will be allocated based on TA preferences.

Students not enrolled in a particular discussion section are welcome to attend other sections unless the room is over-capacity or the TA feels that the room is over capacity, at which point they will be asked to leave.

Office Hours

Office hours for TAs will be in two categories: in person and remote.  Remote office hours will be over Zoom using the CS61A queuing system.  In-person office hours will be conducted outside at a table set up either between Soda and Jacobs hall or on the Wozniak lounge deck, with the particular location to be determined.  The table will include a large umbrella, but if the weather is too bad office hours may be cancelled.

The reason behind this is that physical separation is generally not practical in office hours (and the 6’ rule has far less empirical data backing it than mask wearing does), but there is now significant data that outdoor locations are substantially safer.  Additionally by being outdoors it becomes possible for several students to use a table and talk internally, as we find that student internal discussions are another substantial benefit of office hours.

The instructor will offer in-person office hours in the same location and under the same conditions for all non-confidential office hours.  Confidential issues and remote office hours will be handled over Zoom by appointment.

Exams

Exams will be on-line only, and at the start there will be a time-zone survey.  They will be proctored using whatever tools the University authorizes, so there will almost certainly be zoom proctoring for the final and, if the university will allow it, the midterms as well.

Capacity

We will have capacity limits imposed by the university, and will allocate by limiting registration for in-person activities.  Students who aren’t registered for an in-person discussion or lecture need to leave if over capacity.

Switch to On-Line Only

We are prepared to shift to an on-line only format if the University decides it is necessary.  In addition, if the instructor determines that there appears to be internal spread within the University population the class will shift to online only even if the University decided this is an acceptable risk to students.  As previously noted the concern is not just for the student population (which overall does not seem particularly vulnerable) but students spreading it back to their families and others.
